Narrative:
Exhaustive Round-1 Code Review: HTTP API Integration

This PR introduces HTTP API support via FastAPI/uvicorn. The implementation has **critical correctness and architectural issues**: (1) synchronous blocking server prevents concurrent CLI use, (2) missing port/host validation allows invalid configurations, (3) zero error handling in /hello endpoint, (4) missing type hints and graceful shutdown, and (5) no test coverage. The dependency strategy also adds mandatory FastAPI/uvicorn to all users without optional extras. The blocking I/O pattern in uvicorn.run() directly contradicts the factory's SSH-based remote execution model that may need to coexist with server uptime.

Findings: 10 issues (3 Critical, 5 Warning, 2 Info). Recommend blocking merge until blocking design is resolved and port validation is added.

Findings:
- [Critical] factory/cli.py:106 uvicorn.run() blocks indefinitely; no background daemon mode or async integration available. Users cannot run CLI commands during server uptime.
  description: uvicorn.run() is a blocking call that acquires the event loop indefinitely. This prevents any other CLI commands from executing while the server is running. The factory tool is designed for orchestrating remote tasks, but this architecture forces users to choose between running the HTTP server OR running CLI commands in the same session. This violates the separation of concerns—the CLI should remain responsive and capable of spawning other operations while the server runs in background.
- [Critical] factory/cli.py:98 Port validation missing: no check for 1 ≤ port ≤ 65535. Will silently fail at runtime for invalid ports.
  description: The port option accepts any integer without validation. Valid TCP port range is 1–65535 (port 0 is reserved). Ports < 1024 require root/admin privileges and will cause permission errors. Ports > 65535 are invalid and will silently fail at uvicorn.run() time with cryptic error messages. Users need explicit validation at CLI argument parsing time, not at server startup.
- [Critical] <unknown> Missing HTTP endpoint tests; server is untested and cannot be validated. The /hello endpoint is a single point of failure with zero coverage.
  description: No pytest test suite exists for the /hello endpoint or server lifecycle. There are no fixtures for FastAPI TestClient, no tests for server startup/shutdown, no tests for invalid requests, and no tests for edge cases (e.g., concurrent requests, connection timeouts). The /hello endpoint is untested production code and will regress silently. The review context explicitly notes 'No tests exist yet'.
- [Warning] factory/server.py:9-11 def hello() missing return type hint; use `-> dict[str, str]` or Pydantic model.
  description: The hello() function lacks a return type annotation. FastAPI can infer dict as the return type, but explicit annotations improve code clarity, IDE support, and enable static type checking (mypy). The function should declare `-> dict[str, str]` or use Pydantic response models for schema documentation.
- [Warning] factory/server.py:8-11 No error handling, no explicit status codes, no logging. Endpoint will crash and return 500 on any exception without context.
  description: The endpoint has no try-catch, no validation, and no explicit status code. If any unhandled exception occurs, FastAPI will return a 500 error, but there is no logging or structured error response. The response should explicitly set status_code=200 or use FastAPI's status module. Additionally, there is no middleware for error handling, request logging, or exception tracing.
- [Warning] factory/cli.py:101-106 uvicorn.run() has no exception handler; binding errors will crash CLI with raw traceback.
  description: The serve() function has no try-catch around uvicorn.run(). If the server fails to bind to the port (e.g., address already in use, permission denied), the exception will crash the CLI with a traceback instead of a user-friendly error message. HTTP binding errors are common and should be caught and reported.
- [Warning] factory/cli.py:106 No explicit SIGTERM/SIGINT handling; shutdown may leave orphaned processes or incomplete requests.
  description: uvicorn.run() does not explicitly configure signal handlers. While uvicorn has built-in SIGINT handling, there is no guarantee of clean shutdown, resource cleanup, or logging of shutdown events. The review context lists this as a concern for proper lifecycle management.
- [Warning] factory/cli.py:97-99 Host parameter not validated; invalid values fail silently at runtime.
  description: The host option accepts any string without validation. Invalid hostnames (e.g., 'localhost' vs '127.0.0.1'), IPv6 addresses, or malformed inputs will silently fail at uvicorn.run() time. FastAPI will attempt to bind and fail, but validation should happen at CLI argument level.
- [Warning] pyproject.toml:16-17 FastAPI/uvicorn are mandatory; should be optional via extras_require for CLI-only users.
  description: fastapi and uvicorn are listed in the main dependencies list, making them mandatory for all users. However, users who only use the CLI (factory run, factory poll, etc.) don't need the HTTP server. This adds ~5 transitive dependencies to every installation. Python packaging best practice is to use extras_require for optional features: `pip install silverpond-factory[server]`.
- [Info] factory/server.py:5 app = FastAPI() at module level creates side effects on import; consider lazy initialization.
  description: The FastAPI app is instantiated at module level (line 5) during import. This means every import of factory.server creates a new app instance. If factory.server is imported in multiple places or if there are test utilities that import it, multiple app instances will exist in memory. It's minor but violates the principle of lazy initialization.
- [Info] factory/cli.py:104-105 Server startup messages use typer.echo; should use logging module for structured logs.
  description: The serve() command uses typer.echo() for informational messages instead of the logging module. This inconsistent with observability best practices. The factory codebase should use a logging framework (logging or loguru) to provide consistent, filterable logs with timestamps and log levels. Server startup/shutdown messages are critical operational events that should be logged structurally.

