      "body": "## Crucible Review Summary\n\n- Issues: 11\n- Critical: 5, Warning: 4\n\n### Top Actions\n- [Critical] No HTTP endpoint or server tests; untested API layer (<unknown>)\n- [Critical] Zero test coverage for HTTP server endpoints (<unknown>)\n- [Critical] Zero test coverage for HTTP server and endpoints (<unknown>)\n- [Critical] Port parameter lacks bounds validation (factory/cli.py:98)\n- [Critical] Synchronous blocking server prevents concurrent CLI operation (factory/cli.py:106)\n- [Warning] Host parameter accepts any string; no validation for IP/hostname format (factory/cli.py:97)\n- [Warning] Host parameter accepts any string without IP/hostname validation (factory/cli.py:97)\n- [Warning] Missing return type annotation on hello() endpoint (factory/server.py:9)\n- [Warning] FastAPI/uvicorn are mandatory dependencies without optional extras (pyproject.toml:16)\n\n### Notable Issues\n- **No HTTP endpoint or server tests; untested API layer** `<unknown>`: The /hello endpoint and HTTP server have zero test coverage. No pytest fixtures, no FastAPI TestClient usage, no startup/shutdown scenario tests. This is a single point of failure—the endpoint could crash, return 500 errors, or have logic bugs and they would not be caught until runtime in production. Given the new HTTP attack surface (network accessibility vs. CLI-only), testing is mandatory.\n- **Zero test coverage for HTTP server endpoints** `<unknown>`: No pytest test suite exists for the /hello endpoint or server lifecycle. There are no fixtures for FastAPI TestClient, no tests for server startup/shutdown, no tests for invalid requests, and no tests for edge cases (e.g., concurrent requests, connection timeouts). The /hello endpoint is untested production code and will regress silently. The review context explicitly notes 'No tests exist yet'.\n- **Zero test coverage for HTTP server and endpoints** `<unknown>`: No pytest test suite exists for the /hello endpoint or server lifecycle. There are no FastAPI TestClient fixtures, no tests for server startup/shutdown, invalid requests, or edge cases. The /hello endpoint is untested production code. Given the new HTTP attack surface (network accessibility vs. CLI-only), testing is mandatory to prevent silent regressions.\n- **Port parameter lacks bounds validation** `factory/cli.py:98`: The port option accepts any integer without validation. Valid TCP port range is 1–65535 (port 0 is reserved). Ports < 1024 require root/admin privileges and will cause permission errors. Ports > 65535 are invalid and will silently fail at uvicorn.run() time with cryptic error messages. Users need explicit validation at CLI argument parsing time, not at server startup.\n- **Synchronous blocking server prevents concurrent CLI operation** `factory/cli.py:106`: uvicorn.run() is a blocking call that acquires the event loop indefinitely. This prevents any other CLI commands from executing while the server is running. The factory tool is designed for orchestrating remote tasks, but this architecture forces users to choose between running the HTTP server OR running CLI commands in the same session. This violates the separation of concerns—the CLI should remain responsive and capable of spawning other operations while the server runs in background.\n- **Host parameter accepts any string; no validation for IP/hostname format** `factory/cli.py:97`: The host parameter at line 97 is declared as `str = typer.Option(\"127.0.0.1\", \"--host\", \"-h\", help=\"Host to bind to\")` with no validation. Users can pass arbitrary strings (e.g., `--host ';;;;'`, `--host ../../../etc/passwd`, or invalid IPs like `256.256.256.256`) which will silently fail at runtime when uvicorn attempts to bind. No validation-time feedback is provided.\n- **Host parameter accepts any string without IP/hostname validation** `factory/cli.py:97`: The host parameter accepts arbitrary strings with no validation. Users can pass invalid values (e.g., `--host ';;;;'`, `256.256.256.25